Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
query_power_data(25.10)                                query_power_data(25.10)

Name
       query_power_data - The query_power_data command allows you to query the
       binary  current  files  (.ptiavg/.ptipeak)  that Power Calculation/Rail
       Analysis creates

Syntax
       query_power_data

       [-help]

       [<<in_file> <<file1>[<file2>] ...>>]

       [-average_current]

       [-clock_average]

       [-dump_pwl]

       [-frame <<string>>]

       [-instance_list <<inst_list>>]

       [-instance_list_file <filename>]

       [-list]

       [-output <<string>>]

       [-peak_current]

       [-peak_time]

       [-pin]

       [-time_steps]

       [-stdout]

       [-total_current <<input_current_file>>]

       [-output_tap_name <<tap_name>>]

       The query_power_data command allows you to  query  the  binary  current
       files  (.ptiavg/.ptipeak) that Power Calculation/Rail Analysis creates.
       It reads the tap current data in the current files and reports  various
       information for debugging.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs the command usage and a brief description about the com-
              mand parameters.

       <<in_file> <<file1>[<file2>] ...>>
              Specifies  the  names  of  the  VDD and VSS instance voltage pti
              files.

       -average_current
              Specifies to write the average current of all instances.

       -clock_average
              Specifies to write the clock based current report.

       -dump_pwl
              Specifies to write the tap current in the PWL  format.  You  can
              use this parameter to view the contents of the binary data file.

       -frame <<string>>
              Specifies intervals for the clock_average report.

       -instance_list <<inst_list>>
              Specify  the list of instances to be dumped in the ASCII format,
              one instance per line. If  not  specified,  it  prints  all  in-
              stances.  The  -instance_list  parameter  is  specified with the
              -dump_pwl, -peak_current, -peak_time, and-average_current  para-
              meters.

       -instance_list_file <filename>
              Specifies  a file with the list of instances to be dumped in the
              ASCII format.

       -list  Specifies to write the tap names from the input file.

       -output <<string>>
              Specifies the name of the output file.

       -output_tap_name <<tap_name>>
              Specifies the name of the output tap in the  new  current  file,
              which is created using the -total_current parameter.

       -peak_current
              Specifies to write the peak current of all instances

       -peak_time
              Specifies to write the peak current time of all instances.

       -pin   Specifies  to  print  the pin names with the instance names. The
              -pin parameter is specified with the  -dump_pwl and  -list para-
              meters.

       -stdout
              Specifies to print the report to standard output.

       -time_steps
              Specifies to summarize the minimum current, maximum current, av-
              erage current, and total current for each interval in  the  data
              file.  You  can  use  this  data to estimate which interval in a
              transient response might contain the worst-case data.

       -total_current <<input_current_file> <output_total_current_file>>
              Specifies to create a new current (.ptiavg) file containing  the
              total  current for all taps of a net. This parameter can be used
              if you have a very large current file  generated  by  the  Power
              Calculation engine and want to see only a total current waveform
              in the SimVision waveform viewer.

              <input_current_file>  is  the  current file that will be read in
              (output from the Power Calculation engine).

              Use the following syntax to create a total current file:

              query_power_data -total_current <<input_current_file>>   -output
              <<output_total_current_file>>

              -output  is  used to specify a user-defined output current file-
              name, and is not a mandatory parameter. If  not  specified,  the
              output file will be generated automatically with the name of the
              input file suffixed with .ptiavg.

Example
              * The  following  command  creates a total current waveform file
                VDD from the input file dynamic_VDD.ptiavg:

                query_power_data -output_tap_name vdd_tap  -total_current  dy-
                namic_VDD.ptiavg -output VDD

